'''Gliese 412''' is a pair of stars that share a [[common proper motion]] through space and are thought to form a [[binary star]] system. The pair have an angular separation of 31.4″ at a [[position angle]] of 126.1°.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Gould, Andrew |author2=Chanamé, Julio | title=New Hipparcos-based Parallaxes for 424 Faint Stars | journal=The Astrophysical Journal Supplement Series | volume=150 | issue=2 | pages=455–464 |date=February 2004 | doi=10.1086/381147 | bibcode=2004ApJS..150..455G|arxiv = astro-ph/0309001 }}</ref> They are located 15.8 [[light year]]s distant from the [[Sun]] in the [[constellation]] [[Ursa Major]]. Both components are relatively dim [[red dwarf]] stars.
The two stellar components of this system have a [[projected separation]] of about 152&nbsp;[[Astronomical Unit|AU]], and an estimated orbital [[semimajor axis]] of 190&nbsp;AU.<ref name="apj113">{{cite journal |author1=Reid, I. Neill |author2=Gizis, John E. | title=Low-Mass Binaries and the Stellar Luminosity Function |date=June 1997 | journal=Astronomical Journal | volume=113 | pages=2246–2269 | doi=10.1086/118436 | bibcode=1997AJ....113.2246R }}</ref> The primary has about 48% of the [[Solar mass|Sun's mass]], while the secondary is only 10%.<ref name="RECONS">{{cite web | url=http://www.astro.gsu.edu/RECONS/TOP100.posted.htm | accessdate=2009-09-14 | title=The 100 nearest star systems | publisher=[[Research Consortium On Nearby Stars]] | date=2009-09-14 }}</ref> The primary has a projected [[stellar rotation|rotation]] velocity at the [[equator]] of less than 3&nbsp;km/s; the secondary has a rotation velocity of {{Val|7.7|1.7}}&nbsp;km/s.<ref name="aaa331">{{cite journal | author=Delfosse, X. |display-authors=etal | title=Rotation and chromospheric activity in field M dwarfs | journal=Astronomy and Astrophysics | volume=331 | pages=581–595 |date=March 1998 | bibcode=1998A&A...331..581D }}</ref>
The primary star was monitored for [[radial velocity]] (RV) variations caused by a Jupiter-mass companion in a short period orbit. It displayed no significant excess of RV variation that could be attributed to a planet.<ref>{{cite journal | author=Endl, Michael |display-authors=etal | title=Exploring the Frequency of Close-in Jovian Planets around M Dwarfs |date=September 2006 | journal=The Astrophysical Journal | volume=649 | issue=1 | pages=436–443 | doi=10.1086/506465 | bibcode=2006ApJ...649..436E|arxiv = astro-ph/0606121 }}</ref> A search of the system using near-infrared speckle interferometry also failed to detect a companion orbiting at distances of 1–10 AU.<ref>{{cite journal | author=Leinert, C. |display-authors=etal | title=A search for companions to nearby southern M dwarfs with near-infrared speckle interferometry | journal=Astronomy and Astrophysics | volume=325 | pages=159–166 |date=September 1997 | bibcode=1997A&A...325..159L }}</ref> Nor has a [[brown dwarf]] been detected orbiting within this system.<ref>{{cite journal | author=Oppenheimer, B. R. |display-authors=etal | title=A Coronagraphic Survey for Companions of Stars within 8 Parsecs |date=April 2001 | journal=The Astronomical Journal | volume=121 | issue=4 | pages=2189–2211 | doi=10.1086/319941 | bibcode=2001AJ....121.2189O|arxiv = astro-ph/0101320 }}</ref>
The [[Space velocity (astronomy)|space velocity]] components of this system are U = 141, V = –7 and W = 7. They are members of the halo population of the [[Milky Way]] galaxy.<ref name="aaa331"/>
==X-ray source==
The secondary is a [[flare star]] that is referred to as WX Ursae Majoris. It is characterized as a UV Ceti type variable star that displays infrequent increases in luminosity. This star was observed to flare as early as 1939 by the Dutch astronomer [[Adriaan van Maanen]].<ref>{{cite journal | last=Joy | first=Alfred H. |date=June 1967 | title=Stellar Flares | journal=Astronomical Society of the Pacific Leaflets | volume=10 | issue=456 | pages=41–48 | bibcode=1967ASPL...10...41J }}</ref>
Component B (WX Ursae Majoris) has been identified as an X-ray source, while no significant X-ray emission was detected from component A.<ref name=Schmitt>{{ cite journal |author1=Schmitt JHMM |author2=Fleming TA |author3=Giampapa MS |title=The X-Ray View of the Low-Mass Stars in the Solar Neighborhood |journal=Astrophys. J. |date=September 1995 |volume=450 |issue=9 |pages=392–400 |bibcode=1995ApJ...450..392S |doi=10.1086/176149 }}</ref> This system had not been studied in X-rays prior to [[ROSAT]].<ref name=Schmitt/>
