'''Thoriated glass''' is a [[glass]] material used in the manufacture of optical systems, specifically [[Camera lens|photographic lenses]]. It is useful to this process due to its high [[refractive index]]. Thoriated glass is [[radioactive]] due to the inclusion of [[thorium dioxide]], oxide of radioactive element [[thorium]]. It has therefore been succeeded as a material of choice by glass including [[lanthanum oxide]]. Thoriated glass can contain up to 30% by weight of thorium.<ref name="McMillan">http://www.irpa.net/irpa3/cdrom/VOL.3B/W3B_13.PDF Robert C. McMillan & Steven A. Horne: ''Eye Exposure from Thoriated Optical Glass'' (U.S. Army memo)</ref> The thoriated glass elements in lenses over time develop a brown tint reducing transmission and interfering with neutral color reproduction.
Many Kodak and Takumar lenses that were produced prior to the 1960s are radioactive.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dsider.co.uk/bills-blogs/radioactive-camera-lenses/|title=Radioactive Camera Lenses from the recent past|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref>
==Radiation browning== Over extended time periods, thoriated glass may develop significant discoloration. This is due to induced [[F-center|F-centers]] forming in the glass as the [[radioactive decay]] of the thorium progresses.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=J0RX1mbhzAEC&dq=radiation+browning&source=gbs_navlinks_s|title=The Properties of Optical Glass|last=Bach|first=Hans|last2=Neuroth|first2=Norbert|date=1998-08-06|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|isbn=9783540583578|language=en}}</ref> The formation of F-centers is due to the [[ionizing]] effect of the high energy thorium decay products. This process can potentially be reversed by [[Annealing (glass)|annealing]] the glass or exposing it to [[light]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sealandair.fr/pdf/birns-nucleaire/camera-lights/radiation-induced-discoloration.pdf|title=Radiation-induced Discoloration|last=|first=|date=|website=www.sealandair.fr|publisher=BIRNS, Inc .|access-date=}}</ref>
